#Since no daily rate, hourly rate, and monthly rate were not significant we will not use them for future analysis of attrition contributors.
percent <- data2 %>% group_by(Attrition) %>% summarize(count=n(), quit = n()/nrow(data2))

percent %>% ggplot(aes(x=2, y=quit, fill=Attrition)) + geom_col() + ggtitle("Percentage of Attrition") + theme(axis.title = element_blank(), axis.ticks = element_blank(), axis.text = element_blank())

JobRole_perc <- data2 %>% group_by(JobRole) %>% summarize(count=n(), RolePercentage = n()/nrow(data2))

#K-Nearest Neighbor attrition analysis: create training and test set from the data
data3$StockOptionLevel = as.factor(data3$StockOptionLevel)
data3$Attrition=as.factor(data3$Attrition)
data4 <- data3
levels(data4$Attrition) <- c("No", "Yes")

Att_whole <- createDataPartition(as.factor(data4$Attrition), p=.8, list = F)
Att_train <- data4[Att_whole,]
Att_test <- data4[-Att_whole,]
TCKnn = trainControl(
  method = "repeatedcv", 
  number = 5, 
  repeats = 20,
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary, 
  classProbs = TRUE)

attrition_knn <- train(Attrition ~ ., data = Att_train, method = "knn", metric = "Spec",  trControl = TCKnn, preProcess = c("center","scale"), tuneLength = 6
)

#Test data
Att_test$attrit_knn = predict(attrition_knn, newdata = Att_test)

confusionMatrix(table(Att_test$Attrition, Att_test$attrit_knn))
